Look at the console (the thing with the knobs). If there are visible screws, remove them. If not, slide off the end caps to expose screws, and remove them. Remove the clamps for the motor and from the machine.Support the weight of the motor with your spare hand. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Pull console forward and up to remove the tabs on the bottom of the console from the holes on the top of the cabinet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4a/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Lift up the console and lay it back until it rests on the hinges. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Disconnect the lid switch harness connector by pressing on the tab (located in the middle), and pulling up. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/45/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/45/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Insert a screwdriver into the turned-up edge of the clip (located on both sides), and pry back. This removes the clip from the hole in the cabinet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/68/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Slide the other end of the clip down and out the slot in the rear panel. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Do the same thing to the other clip. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/61/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet7.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/61/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet7.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Open and hold the lid while grabbing the cabinet front opening. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b8/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet8.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet8.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b8/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet8.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Tilt the top of the cabinet toward you by pulling on the lid and opening of the cabinet. This releases the back slots of the cabinet from the tabs in the back of the base. Be sure that the back edge clears the vacuum break. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet9.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet9.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet9.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet9.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using the back of your leg and/or body as a support for the front of the cabinet, carefully lift while pulling it away from the base of the washer. This releases the front slots of the cabinet from the tabs in the front of the base. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet10.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet10.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7f/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet10.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet10.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Set the cabinet aside{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet11.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet11.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet11.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet11.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using a screwdriver or your hand, unsnap the bottom retainer from the pump. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/68\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/68\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Using pliers, slide the clamp on the top hose off the port of the pump. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/9a\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/9a\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Carefully remove this hose. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8d\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8d\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Using a pail, drain excess water from this hose. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-3Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Using pliers, slide the clamp on the bottom hose off the port of the pump. Carefully remove this hose. Using a pail, drain the excess water from this hose.

Using a screwdriver, remove the screws (if used) which hold the top and bottom retainers to the front of the drive motor. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/40/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/40/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Using a screwdriver or your hand, unsnap the bottom retainer from the drive motor. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/94/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/94/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Carefully pull the drive motor straight out. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

