 Unplug washer or disconnect power.  Turn off the water to the washer. (Do NOT skip this step if you are going to completely remove the water pump down the line.) Pull the machine out far enough to tip it back against the wall. (Make sure to over center the CG behind the back legs when you tip it back or brace the front end up in the air.) Disconnect the wire harness from the motor. (Both the connecter and the separate wire.) Remove the two snap clamps from the water pump (Do NOT disconnect the water lines or you will have a bit of mess). Stowe the pump up out of the way. Mine fit nicely above the plate above its location.Remove the two pump clamps from the motor. Remove the cabinet from the base: Look at the console (the thing with the knobs). If there are visible screws, remove them. If not, slide off the end caps to expose screws, and remove them. Remove the clamps for the motor and from the machine.Support the weight of the motor with your spare hand. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Repair-the-Motor-Coupler-in-a-Kenmore-Washer-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
